00:13:41,940 --> 00:13:45,260
How to get started in user experience design 

177
00:13:45,460 --> 00:13:51,100
To which my response is always that nothing can substitute real world experience 

178
00:13:51,900 --> 00:13:56,500
Building the skills required of a user experience designer takes time 

179
00:13:56,660 --> 00:13:58,820
Patience and commitment 

180
00:13:59,450 --> 00:14:03,890
Higher education is a great way to equip yourself with some core skills 

181
00:14:03,960 --> 00:14:06,920
But it will not prepare you for actual challenges

182
00:14:06,920 --> 00:14:08,760
You'll face with clients work 

183
00:14:09,480 --> 00:14:10,720
In other words 

184
00:14:10,840 --> 00:14:13,350
Being proficient with a design tool

185
00:14:13,350 --> 00:14:17,900
And the few methods doesn't make you a user experience designer 

186
00:14:18,380 --> 00:14:21,700
There simply isn't a one size fits all process 

187
00:14:22,260 --> 00:14:25,100
Being effective requires adaptability 

188
00:14:25,660 --> 00:14:28,140
Something you don't really learn in school 

189
00:14:28,430 --> 00:14:31,710
Much less in a sixth month training camp 

190
00:14:32,240 --> 00:14:34,800
It's gained through experience on the job

191
00:14:34,880 --> 00:14:38,560
And learning what's appropriate given the needs of the project 

192
00:14:39,170 --> 00:14:43,250
i found my way to user experience through graphic design 

193
00:14:43,450 --> 00:14:45,210
And slowly over many

194
00:14:45,450 --> 00:14:51,160
Different roles and experiences that led me to become a user experience designer 

195
00:14:51,650 --> 00:14:55,250
it took time and commitment to continue to pursue 

196
00:14:55,250 --> 00:14:59,490
roles within teams that i knew could teach and challenge me 

197
00:15:00,010 --> 00:15:03,330
That's not to say that i think my path is the only one 

